## 7.2.2 Definition of the Base Features and Binned Data

### Purpose
This subsection defines the bin-level variables used for model fitting.

### Setup / formulation
The data are binned with bin size $\delta t = 10s$.

For each bin $[t,t+\delta t]$:

- $\mathrm{ofi}_t$ is the sum of all OFI event contributions in the bin.
- $q_t$ is the trade imbalance in the bin, using trades only.
- $P_t$ is the observed midprice at the bin start.
- The bin return is:

$$
r_t = \frac{P_{t+\delta t}}{P_t} - 1.
$$

- $|q_t|$ is the amount of volume traded in the bin.
- $d_t$ is the average order-book depth over the bin.

### Main result
The chapter separates all-event OFI, $\mathrm{ofi}_t$, from trade-only imbalance, $q_t$.

### Interpretation
OFI is richer and more predictive at short horizons because it uses order-book events beyond trades. Trade-only imbalance is more natural for execution models because it corresponds more directly to actions by a trading algorithm.

