## 7.2.3 Definition of the Time Kernel and Price Impact Computation

### Purpose
This subsection defines the time-decay mechanism used to convert order flow into an impact state.

### Setup / formulation
The chapter studies an exponential time kernel under multiple clocks.

The instantaneous market activity state $v_t$ is defined as an exponentially decaying sum of traded volume:

$$
v_{t+\delta t} - v_t = -\beta v_t \delta t + |q_t|.
$$

The impact state $I_t$ is computed model-by-model using similar exponentially decaying recursions.

### Main result
The exponential kernel provides a tractable common structure for comparing transient impact models across clocks and horizons.

### Interpretation
Past trades continue to affect prices, but their effect decays over time. The decay speed is controlled by $\beta$, often expressed through the half-life $\log 2 / \beta$.

