## 7.3.1 The Order Flow Imbalance Model

### Purpose
This subsection introduces OFI as an event-based price impact and short-horizon alpha model.

### Setup / formulation
The original OFI model does not use a time-decay kernel:

$$
I_{t+h} - I_t
=
\lambda \sigma
\sum_{s=t}^{t+h-\delta t}
\frac{\mathrm{ofi}_s}{ADV}.
$$

OFI includes:

- trades;
- limit order submissions;
- limit order cancellations.

### Main result
OFI strongly predicts short-horizon returns and often outperforms trade-only impact models in $R^2$.

### Interpretation
OFI is powerful because it summarizes all directional order-book pressure, not just executed trades. However, it is less suited to optimal execution because it does not directly answer trading counterfactuals.

