## 7.4.3 Across Clocks

### Purpose
This subsection studies whether impact models should be expressed under regular time, volume time, or another market-activity clock.

### Setup / formulation
Under a volume clock, time changes according to traded volume rather than calendar time.

To compare half-lives across clocks, the chapter normalizes the clock so that average half-lives match. For example, in the volume clock, an expected one-minute half-life corresponds to:

$$
\frac{\log 2}{\beta}
=
\frac{ADV}{390},
$$

because there are $390$ minutes in a US trading day.

The prediction horizon $h$ remains in regular time in this subsection.

### Main result
Volume-clock models perform roughly on par with regular-clock models when predicting regular-clock horizons.

### Interpretation
The right clock depends on the application. Some strategies naturally operate in regular time, while others slow down or speed up with market activity.

