## 7.4.4 Across Stocks

### Purpose
This subsection compares universal models with stock-specific models and studies order-level concavity using public data.

### Setup / formulation
Two fitting approaches are compared:

- Universal models pool normalized data across stocks.
- Specialized models fit a separate model per stock.

The chapter also defines the end-of-day imbalance proxy:

$$
\mathrm{imb}
=
\frac{\sum_t q_t}{\sum_t |q_t|}.
$$

This is used as a public-tape proxy for sizable day-order imbalance.

### Main result
Specialized models perform better in-sample by construction. For most non-OFI models, universal models perform better out-of-sample.

For the imbalance diagnostic:

- for all models except AFS, $\lambda$ decreases with imbalance, indicating global concavity not captured by those models;
- AFS is too concave under this diagnostic, with $\lambda$ increasing as a function of imbalance.

### Interpretation
Universal models are stable benchmarks and allow data-intensive diagnostics that are impossible stock-by-stock. Public-tape imbalance is only a proxy for order size, so prediction bias may affect conclusions.

