## 7.5.1 Causal Bias for Cross-Impact

### Purpose
This subsection explains why pairwise cross-impact estimates may be causally biased.

### Setup / formulation
For stocks $i$ and $j$, define:

- returns $\Delta P_i$, $\Delta P_j$;
- public trading tapes $Q_i$, $Q_j$;
- underlying trading strategies $S_i$, $S_j$;
- basket strategy $\bar S$.

The pairwise cross-impact counterfactual is:

$$
\mathbb{E}[\Delta P_j \mid do(Q_i)].
$$

Under causal structure $\mathcal{C}$, naive conditioning is biased:

$$
\mathbb{E}[\Delta P_j \mid do(Q_i)]
\neq
\mathbb{E}[\Delta P_j \mid Q_i].
$$

Conditioning on the basket strategy identifies the counterfactual:

$$
\mathbb{E}[\Delta P_j \mid do(Q_i)]
=
\int
\mathbb{E}[\Delta P_j \mid Q_i, \bar S=s]
p(\bar S=s)
\, ds.
$$

### Main result
The common basket strategy $\bar S$ opens a back-door path between $Q_i$ and $\Delta P_j$. Adjusting for $\bar S$ closes the path.

### Interpretation
If two stocks are traded together, observing trades in one stock may predict returns in another even without direct cross-impact. Pairwise regressions can therefore overstate causal cross-impact.

