## 7.5.2.2 Distinction Between $do(Q_i,Q_j)$ and $do(\bar Q)$

### Purpose
This subsection clarifies which intervention is appropriate for factor-mediated cross-impact.

### Setup / formulation
Suppose a trade of size $q$ in stock $i$ decomposes into:

$$
q = q_i + \bar q,
$$

where:

- $q_i$ is the factor-neutral component;
- $\bar q$ is the factor component.

A one-period toy model is:

$$
I^i(Q^i) = \lambda^i Q^i,
$$

$$
\bar I(\bar Q) = \bar \lambda \bar Q,
$$

$$
\Delta P^i = I^i + \rho^i \bar I + \epsilon.
$$

The correct intervention for a non-factor-neutral trade is:

$$
do(Q_i=q_i,\bar Q=\bar q),
$$

not:

$$
do(Q_i=q).
$$

The resulting impact is:

$$
\mathbb{E}[\Delta P^i \mid do(Q_i=q_i,\bar Q=\bar q)]
=
\lambda^i q_i + \rho^i \bar \lambda \bar q.
$$

### Main result
Applying the stock-specific impact model to the full order size is inconsistent with the EigenLiquidity causal structure.

### Interpretation
A trade must be decomposed into factor-neutral and factor components. Each component has its own impact channel.

