## 7.5.2.4 Cross-Impact for Risk Management and Factor Research

### Purpose
This subsection explains how factor-mediated cross-impact affects transaction costs and risk models.

### Setup / formulation
Factor-level impact:

$$
\bar Q \rightarrow \Delta \bar P
$$

directly models factor trading costs.

For factor model estimation, trades confound the effect of factor returns on stock returns through the path:

$$
\Delta \bar P \leftarrow \bar Q \rightarrow Q_j \rightarrow \Delta P_j.
$$

The adjustment formula is:

$$
\mathbb{E}[\Delta P_j \mid do(\Delta \bar P)]
=
\int
\mathbb{E}[\Delta P_j \mid \Delta \bar P,\bar Q=q]
p(\bar Q=q)
\, dq.
$$

Naive identification fails:

$$
\mathbb{E}[\Delta P_j \mid do(\Delta \bar P)]
\neq
\mathbb{E}[\Delta P_j \mid \Delta \bar P].
$$

### Main result
Observed covariance matrices blend fundamental correlations and flow-based correlations.

### Interpretation
During liquidity crises, flow-based correlations can rise sharply even if fundamental relationships are unchanged. Risk models that ignore this distinction can underestimate endogenous market risk.

