## 7.5.3.2 Options in Said et al.

### Purpose
This subsection reviews price impact in options markets.

### Setup / formulation
Said et al. define option metaorders by grouping trades with common characteristics, including direction with respect to an implied-volatility parameter $\theta$.

The signed sensitivity is based on:

$$
S^\theta = s \times Q \times \frac{\partial O}{\partial \theta},
$$

where:

- $s$ is trade sign;
- $Q$ is quantity;
- $O$ is option price;
- $\theta$ may represent volatility level or skew.

The two main factors are:

- at-the-money forward volatility level;
- at-the-money forward skew.

### Main result
Options impact is concave at the order level, with exponents close to the square-root law.

### Interpretation
Options cross-impact is naturally factor-based: trades affect volatility-surface level and skew rather than only individual option prices.

