## 7.6.1 Discrete Formulas for Price Impact Models

### Purpose
This subsection lists the central discrete-time model equations.

### Setup / formulation

#### OW model

$$
I_{t+\delta t} - I_t
=
-\beta I_t \delta t
+
\lambda \sigma \frac{q_t}{ADV}.
$$

#### Locally concave Bouchaud model

$$
I_{t+\delta t} - I_t
=
-\beta I_t \delta t
+
\lambda \sigma \operatorname{sign}(q_t)
\sqrt{\frac{|q_t|}{ADV}}.
$$

#### Reduced-form model

$$
I_{t+\delta t} - I_t
=
-\beta I_t \delta t
+
\frac{\lambda \sigma q_t}{\sqrt{ADV \cdot v_t}}.
$$

#### AFS model

$$
I_t
=
\lambda \sigma \operatorname{sign}(J_t)\sqrt{|J_t|},
$$

where:

$$
J_{t+\delta t} - J_t
=
-\beta J_t \delta t
+
\frac{q_t}{ADV}.
$$

### Main result
These four models form the chapter’s core single-stock model comparison.

### Interpretation
OW is linear and transient. Bouchaud is locally concave. Reduced-form adjusts for dynamic liquidity. AFS is globally concave through the latent state $J_t$.

