## 7.6.3 The EigenLiquidity Model

### Purpose
This subsection summarizes the chapter’s central cross-impact model.

### Setup / formulation
The EigenLiquidity model captures the idea:

- assets that trade together move together.

For stocks $i,j$:

- returns are $\Delta P_i$, $\Delta P_j$;
- factor return is $\Delta \bar P$;
- stock trades are $Q_i$, $Q_j$;
- factor flow is $\bar Q$.

Cross-impact travels through the factor:

$$
\bar Q \rightarrow \Delta \bar P \rightarrow \Delta P_i,\Delta P_j.
$$

### Main result
Conditional on factor impact, stock-level price impacts are independent.

### Interpretation
The economically important object is not necessarily pairwise stock-to-stock impact. It is often the impact of trading common factors.

